    "summary": "KEEP \"impels\" — Chinese originals are genuinely different (想要 vs 推动)",
    "content": "**KEEP \"impels\"** in footnote [^3].\n\nThe Chinese originals are genuinely different:\n\n- **Body text**: 使得我**想要**去如何如何地对待他人 — \"makes me *want to*...\" (想要 = want to, softer, volitional)\n- **Footnote [^3]**: 这个感受使得（**推动**）我去做一些行为 — \"this feeling makes (*pushes/drives*) me to do...\" (推动 = push/drive, stronger, quasi-mechanical)\n\nThe footnote is where the author introduces the technical term 推动力 (driving force / motivation). The author deliberately uses stronger language here — 推动 in parentheses is an intensifier glossing 使得, building toward the 推动力 concept in the very next sentence. \"Impels\" captures this force accurately (impel = to drive or push forward). Harmonizing to \"moves\" would flatten a distinction the author intentionally draws.\n\nThe difference is philosophically meaningful: in the body text, the feeling makes me *want* (volitional, first-person); in the footnote, the feeling *drives/pushes* me (quasi-causal, building toward the \"motivation\" concept). \"Moves\" vs \"impels\" correctly mirrors this distinction."
  }
